    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee> <placeName>Walnut St 371</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName><hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi></placeName></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><placeName>Baltimore</placeName>&#44; the 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of</p>
          <p><date>Shevat &#40;December&#44; 1848&#41;</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I should gladly reply to your last<lb/> letter and the question you ask me there&#8212;how do<lb/> &#42;I like Zung&#63; But the many troubles&#44; physical<lb/> and spiritual which I am undergoing&#44; leave<lb/> me little time to write. Just today&#44; however<add>&#63;</add><lb/> have a bit of time. And I would like to make<lb/> this one remark. I have read the work with a<lb/> great deal of effort. I say&#44; &#8220;with effort&#8221; because<lb/> such works&#44; in which the footnotes make up more<lb/> than the strength&#44; wear one out. And what do<lb/> you think have I gained after all this effort&#63;<lb/> Not a thing. Our German gentleman doctors un&#45;<lb/>fortunately suffer&#44; all of them&#44; from a certain disease&#44;<lb/> so take the holiest subject and drop them down<lb/> with Greek and Latin criticism into the lowest<lb/> depths. The introduce strange ideas where<lb/> there have no application and no foundation.<lb/> According to this work&#44; the Bible is no more Bible<lb/> and everything built upon it is certainly worth&#45;<lb/>less. God protect us against all these doctors&#44;<lb/> whose medicine chest is full of poison.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I was particularly amused in your<lb/> last occident&#44; of <date>Rosh C<add>&#63;</add>desh Tebet</date>&#44; by a notice</p>
			<p>&#42;The reference is probably to <persName>Leopold Zung&#39;s</persName> &#8220;Zur<lb/> Geschichte und Literatur&#44;&#8221; published <date>1845</date>.</p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p>of the clergyman <persName>Pazinansky</persName>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">&#40;The rest of this doesn&#39;t seem to make any<lb/> sense. In order to understand it&#44; one would<lb/> have to look up that particular number of the<lb/> Occident to see what this man is talking about.<lb/> In any event&#44; the letter <sic>doesnt</sic> add any&#45;<lb/>thing except to say that that particular notice<lb/> amused the writer&#41;.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In general I have no news. When<lb/> your prayer book is ready you may send<lb/> me two dozen. Perhaps in time I can dis&#45;<lb/>pose of them. Please have them bound.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">He who has mercy upon everyone&#44;<lb/> may He cause truth to grow in our land<lb/> and remove the spirit of <add>&#63;</add> and<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> from us.</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Your friend&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Abraham Reis</persName></p>

          
        </body>
    </text>
